Burden of illness.

McGuire T(1), Wells KB, Bruce ML, Miranda J, Scheffler R, Durham M, Ford DE, 
Lewis L; NIMH Affective Disorders Workgroup.

Author information:
(1)Department of Health Care Policy, Harvard Medical School, 180 Longwood 
Avenue, Boston, Massachusetts 02115-5899, USA. mcguire@hcp.med.harvard.edu

The burden of affective disorders includes costs and the pain and suffering of 
affected individuls. Burden can be perceived from social and private 
perspectives. Although no ideal measure of burden exists, ample evidence 
documents the extensive cost and other negative impacts of affective disorders. 
Affective disorders are associated with disruptive family relations, higher 
health care costs for comorbid conditions, elevated rates of suicide, and lower 
productivity. Reserch should focus on improving measures of burden in general 
and on quantifying burden from the standpoint of diverse population groups.

